[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe repository layout is organized around five isolated layers:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m* Workload Generation: creates reproducible job streams, cluster hardware structures, and historical demand scenarios.[m
[32m+[m[32m* Scheduling Core: exposes a unified interface for pluggable greedy rules, exact optimization models, metaheuristics, and hybrid bounded-time policies, multi-stage stochastic formulations with recourse, and robust optimization models.[m
[32m+[m[32m* Decision Validation and State Management: validates proposed scheduling decisions, applies accepted decisions, starts jobs, keeps waiting jobs queued, releases completed work, and updates cluster state.[m
[32m+[m[32m* Simulation Loop: advances time and repeatedly calls the scheduler to evaluate policy behavior under controlled conditions.[m
[32m+[m[32m* Metrics Layer: measures utilization, queue length, wait time, deadline risk, placement quality, scheduler runtime, and value captured.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 5. Mathematical Starting Point[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe first model is a single-decision scheduling snapshot. At the current scheduling time $t_0$, the scheduler observes the eligible waiting jobs and the currently available GPU capacity. It chooses which jobs start now and how many GPUs each selected job receives from each node.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Sets[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m$$[m
[32m+[m[32m\begin{aligned}[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32mJ &= \text{set of eligible queued jobs}, \\[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32mN &= \text{set of available cluster nodes}.[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32m\end{aligned}[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m$$[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Parameters[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mFor each job $j \in J$:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m$$[m
[32m+[m[32m\begin{aligned}[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32mg_j &= \text{number of GPUs required by job } j, \\[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32md_j &= \text{duration of job } j, \\[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32mp_j &= \text{priority or value of job } j, \\[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32m\ell_j &= \text{deadline of job } j.[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32m\end{aligned}[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m$$[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mFor each node $i \in N$:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m$$[m
[32m+[m[32mc_i = \text{number of currently available GPUs on node } i.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m$$[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe current scheduling time is $t_0$.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Derived Parameters[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mIf job $j$ starts now, its lateness is known before optimization:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m$$[m
[32m+[m[32mL_j = \max \{0; t_0 + d_j - \ell_j\}.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m$$[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe deadline penalty is:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m$$[m
[32m+[m[32mq_j = \beta L_j,[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m$$[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mwhere $\beta \ge 0$ controls how strongly late completion is penalized. When $\beta = 0$, deadline penalties are disabled.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Decision Variables[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m$$[m
[32m+[m[32m\begin{aligned}[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32mx_{ij} &\in \mathbb{Z}_+[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32m&& \text{number of GPUs from node } i \text{ assigned to job } j, \\[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32my_j &\in {0,1}[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32m&& \text{1 if job } j \text{ starts now, 0 otherwise.}[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32m\end{aligned}[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m$$[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Model[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m$$[m
[32m+[m[32m\begin{aligned} \max \quad & \sum_{j \in J} (p_j - q_j)y_j \\[4pt] \text{s.t.} \quad & \sum_{i \in N} x_{ij} = g_j y_j && \forall j \in J, \\[4pt] & \sum_{j \in J} x_{ij} \le c_i && \forall i \in N, \\[4pt] & x_{ij} \in \mathbb{Z}_+ && \forall i \in N, j \in J, \\[4pt] & y_j \in \{0,1\} && \forall j \in J. \end{aligned}[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m$$[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe first constraint enforces all-or-nothing GPU allocation: a job that starts must receive its full GPU demand, while a job that does not start receives no GPUs. The second constraint ensures that the total number of GPUs allocated from any node does not exceed that node’s currently available GPU capacity.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis draft is not yet a full time-indexed scheduling model. It is the smallest clean model needed to define the core allocation decision. Later versions extend the same structure to a planning horizon, topology-aware placement(NVLink vs. InfiniBand hops), GPU types, stochastic scenarios, and decomposition methods.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 6. Scheduling Policies[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mCCO evaluates scheduling policies across a staged progression of complexity:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m* **Greedy baseline:** fast deterministic rules such as shortest processing time, earliest deadline, priority order, or value density. These policies are easy to explain, cheap to run, and useful as both baselines and fallbacks.[m
[32m+[m[32m* **Metaheuristics:** local-search methods such as tabu search, simulated annealing, or large-neighborhood search. These methods can improve placement quality without requiring a full exact solve at every decision point.[m
[32m+[m[32m* **Exact optimization model:** MIP-based formulations used as reference models on small and medium instances. These models clarify the structure of the scheduling problem and provide high-quality solutions when runtime is acceptable.[m
[32m+[m[32m* **Hybrid bounded-time scheduler:** a production-oriented policy that runs a stronger method under a strict time budget and falls back to a fast heuristic when the stronger method is too slow or fails to return a useful solution.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe goal is not to favor one method in isolation. The goal is to compare decision quality, scheduler runtime, queue behavior, and operational impact under the same evaluation harness.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 7. Project Roadmap[m
